<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-983-620  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 983 620.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Engineering  Dec 1989 v21 n12 p22(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Take a close look at EMS and its role in today's manufacturingenvironment. (Engineering Management System)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Laszcz, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An engineering management system (EMS) can automate theengineering release process, thereby providing a major step towardtrue CIM and helping companies save money, time, and manpower.andO;EMSs increase productivity and shorten development cycles bydefining and controlling the release process; improvingscheduling, tracking activities, and communications; reducingdesign redundancy; and providing a central data repository.andP;  Theyalso ensure adherence to policies and procedures.andP;  EMSs includeRequest for Engineering Action (REA) functions that allow users todescribe products or problems.andP;  They enable companies to define arelease process and ensure its compliance, and provide toolsnecessary to create bills of material and classify newly createditems.andP;  EMSs provide a single view of engineering informationthroughout the product life cycle, and are most beneficial whenother systems have access to data in the engineering database.andO;Executives, project managers, application specialists,manufacturing engineers, and engineering data administrators canall benefit from EMSs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EngineeringManagementSystemsEnd UsersManufacturing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>